node.text:
Swipe ➡️ to see @jamesro__ favourite quote from Crying in H Mart and read below why it spoke to him. Then join him in discussing themes found in the book with the author, 8/15/21 at 3pm PDT on @lululemon YouTube Live.

“I’ve never resonated so strongly with a perspective in regards to a physical location. As a Korean-American, I don’t recall many places throughout my childhood that carried parts of my culture like H Mart. It was somewhere I could sit comfortably and feel like myself. There was no expectation to conform to another person’s way of life. I heard the language that was spoken in my house. I smelled the food my parents cooked. I even sensed an aura of peace from others who were experiencing the same. Even to this day, my reasons for going to H Mart haven’t changed – same thoughts, same takeaway. I guess you know at that point, you truly found a piece of home.”

node.text:
The desire for connection is universal. How we make meaning from moments together and time apart echoes the sentiment strongly: Community matters.​
​
To honour this notion three local Vancouver artists—@tierneymilne, @hannaleejoshi, and @priscillayuart—came together to create a vivid mural in the city where lululemon began.​
​
The artwork depicts a celebration of the bonds we share in all their unique facets and styles. Through shifting perspectives, an openness to collaboration, and embracing non-linear movement, beauty is born.​
​
The artwork is now live in front of our Robson Street store in Vancouver, Canada.
